So something I often mention, it was a really fun one to do and I didn't actually get to do it but

00:11:57.159 --> 00:12:07.239
I was leading a statistician on my team who went through it. We at HEB had a method of recruiting

00:12:07.239 --> 00:12:13.000
and when you would apply to a store, you literally apply to that store, a store admin would look at

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
your application, bring in people, interview them, say it sounds great, can you come in tomorrow,

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.320
meet with my store leader at this time, sure, come in, meet. You can imagine it's kind of a

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:24.599
long process, right, and you're getting somebody who's maybe a high school student who's going to

00:12:24.599 --> 00:12:30.119
be checking at the cashier or bagging groceries for, you know, maybe like five, six hours a week.

00:12:30.119 --> 00:12:33.640
So they would go through a lot of this and there's a lot of time in that and the recruiting team had

00:12:33.640 --> 00:12:37.799
always wanted to take that and centralize it. Let us handle all those applications. We can have them

00:12:37.799 --> 00:12:41.880
apply to like several stores at one time and we can move them where we need to and it would

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:46.200
streamline the process and there was a lot of resistance. But when the pandemic happened, they

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:50.119
were like do it. It was just too much stuff going on with running stores, with trying to make sure

00:12:50.119 --> 00:12:55.400
you're managing inventory, hiring folks was just going to take too much time and what they wanted

00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:59.640
to do was understand the impact. It was about six months later, everybody was kind of saying, hey,

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:03.320
maybe we should go back to the way things were. We want to see if we're hiring better quality

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:07.159
folks or not. We didn't really have a measure for quality of hire, like is this person performing

00:13:07.159 --> 00:13:10.919
well or not, but we did want to look at retention. How long are we keeping them because those are

00:13:10.919 --> 00:13:17.880
very high turnover roles. So we ran a survival analysis and we kind of pinned the same time

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:21.640
the previous year when we were running the old process to when we flipped. We looked at how many

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:25.960
people survived like, you know, three months into the role before they left and they left the

00:13:25.960 --> 00:13:31.239
company, not even left to another role. And what we saw was, you know, looking at these two groups,

00:13:31.239 --> 00:13:35.719
this new method actually provided just as good if not better quality candidates. There was a more

00:13:35.719 --> 00:13:42.760
streamlined process allowed for us to hire folks quicker as well and it gave a whole ton more time

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:47.400
back to the stores. And this was used by our director recruiting for all the store leaders

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:51.640
to look at in the presentation she gave out. And they immediately said, okay, great. We surrender,

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:56.119
like you go ahead and do this from now on. Let's figure out a more. Yeah, pretty much. Because,

00:13:56.119 --> 00:13:59.799
you know, when you run a store specifically, it's something like H-E-B, but I think most stores,

00:13:59.799 --> 00:14:04.280
